text: Well you sort of wanted to say something about the— When we first spoke of Jack early on in there and I said that Jack had invited me over and this was in 1975 and that there maybe it was their 76, and I came over and Jack signed some of the books for us, we did a limited edition signed numbered edition and And Jack lives up in the hills there in the Bay Area. And his house, he's up on the side of a hill, and a long, narrow, winding driveway goes up through the trees to his house. I went up and met him and got to know him after a little while. I've been over there a number of times since then just to, I guess, just to visit more than anything else. And I've gotten to know him and his charming wife, Norma, who is kind of one of the background or the basis of the whole thing that goes on over there. They're really a partnership, Jack and Norma, and their son, John, who's 22 or 23 now. The three of them are a family unit, and they work together, and they're very close, the three of them. Jack's... For a fellow who's completely unknown within the field as far as in terms of a personality, no one knows him, and he never goes anywhere. jack's really a social guy and has a number of parties and goes out quite a bit and socializes quite a bit with really a wide variety of people and jack and norma and john and i and And got to be quite good friends. And our friendship was really not, it just started with the book, I guess, and with publishing Jack. But that's just sort of a, it's almost an excuse for us to be together. And we spend a lot of time together. And I'm not even sure what we talk about. A lot of what we talk about is illustration. Jack's a great lover of classical illustration, which is to say of Beardsley and Kay Nielsen and Harry Clark and people who were illustrating at the turn of the century and the early 20th century. And I guess we spend a lot of time talking about that and a lot of time just talking about anything but Jack's work, which we almost never discuss. It never comes up. And last year in Baltimore, Chuck came out here to Pennsylvania, where I am now. I'm here visiting Chuck. And Jack came out and stayed with Chuck for a while. and they got to be good friends. They'd known each other only at a distance, and they spent, actually the three of us spent some time together, or four of us, I should say. Norma was there, and somehow without Norm, Norma's sort of the key to this whole thing in a way that I can't explain, but in any case, Chuck and Chuck's wife and myself and Mara and Jack and Norma just got together and spent a lot of time together. It's an unusual thing when something like a book or I guess a work of art in a sense brings people together and forms the basis of what later becomes very close friendship. Particularly in Jack's case because Jack never discusses his work and doesn't care to. Somehow once he's finished a piece it's as if he's launched a ship and the ship goes and sails away and he's no longer a part of it and that's how he feels of course anyone enjoys recognition in Jack should get more than he does but Jack's life has very little to do with literature except that he writes it he doesn't associate with people who have to do with literature his friends are from all walks of life many of the musicians because jack himself is a musician and enjoys music uh to a great extent you see that in his work you see it showing up in his books from time to time and that's most of what i wanted to say i just want to get a little of the personal in there jack's uh uh uh I've been a good friend and uh uh he's been uh he's been an unusual fellow and he's he's been a it's an unusual kind of uh communication in that and you if you enjoy Jack's works like I do uh would probably have the same sort of relationship or communication because it's with an understanding it's with that understanding of life that that is the reason that you and i both enjoy Jack's work because he sees things a certain way and reacts to things a certain way and just sees a certain colors or whatever in life around him and and uh it's it's uh interesting and a pleasure to communicate with a person like that because you can speak of certain things that normally might never come up in your life. Otherwise, it may never come up in your casual conversation with your friends or your business associates or whatever. Jack and Norma and I and Chuck all share that kind of communication. It's sort of a rare thing and not really something that can be surrounded or defined by words. Okay, that's very good. They said, listen, as long as you brought it up, can I shoot a couple more quick ones at you? Why not? When we spoke to him, I asked him a question about, essentially like what do you want to be remembered for or what's your conception of your own work and so forth. And he replied in this way, and I think he was joking. He said, I want to be remembered as a rich science fiction writer. How would you respond to his conception of his own work? Well, Jack, he's stepping into a role there to avoid a question which I guess any writer might want to avoid. I don't know. I know Jack is offended by artists who take themselves too seriously. And that, as you know, is a real problem with artists and writers today. Once they take themselves seriously, then they're finished, really. most of them are finished as originators or as true artists and so Jack refuses to take himself seriously and does not act like an artist or talk like an artist or whatever as far as a rich science fiction writer I don't know if Jack had wanted to have been rich he could have he did some work in Hollywood and he could have stayed down there or he could have gone through the motions like a lot of other writers and appeared on the shows and publicized his own work and promoted his own work and he didn't do that and that was by personal inclination and by choice so as far as what he wants to be remembered for Jack always says that he wants his work to stand for and by itself and I think he just wants to be remembered for his work. He refuses to pick favorites among his work. I know he likes his Demon Prince series a lot for good reason. He likes the Palace of Love, which is the third in that series. He likes The Eyes of the Overworld, the sequenced stories of the fellow Kugl. And that's probably because Kugl's a rascal, and And Vance himself is a bit of a rascal, and Kugel's even more so. He's the kind of rascal that Vance would like to be if he wasn't such a nice guy at heart. Would he mind if we put a quote like that on our show from you? Oh, not at all. Jack is no— There's no— In fact, if I were to sit here and insult Jack and call the guy a lot of names he would probably enjoy hearing it on the radio simply as a practical joke those kind of situations occur in Jack's book where one person who has helped us to defend himself or reply gets smeared in public or private I won't do that to Jack But Jack certainly would not mind it. Okay listen, also I when I spoke with him near the end of the interview I was asking about his future work and so forth. And he mentioned that book he just finished and what he might have planned. Just in your personal opinion, are there some more really good books that he is going to be writing? I kind of got the impression he wondered if he still had it, if he could still write up to the standards he had set for himself. Well, every writer feels that, particularly when they're not finished with the work. And Jack is finishing up this work, and he's this Lioness, this large fantasy work which takes place on Earth. Lioness is kind of like Avalon. It's some kind of mythical island offshore of Britain somewhere, if you want to locate it. It's sometime in the far past, and it's a magical place with elves and trolls and beings like that. Yeah, I think this is a major work, and I think there will be a few more. Jack's writing fewer books, but he's going to write just a few large, major pieces now. He's kind of done fooling around. One of the reasons he's writing, he was writing all these kind of unrelated books. And these books, they weren't short, but they certainly weren't long. But no one would pay him to do any differently. And he was making money as a writer. And no one would, until Berkeley, gave him a reasonable advance on the work that he's doing now, which allowed him to work for a year or two on it, uninterrupted. I mean, there's economical reasons for this sort of thing. So he was, you know, he finally had the stature and found a publisher that believed in him. Don Wilhelm also has done a good deal for Jack. Put a lot of his books out. got them all back into print but Berkeley will be publishing this particular book and he's been able to do it so he's doing that Jack when he wrote the last two of the Demon Prince books felt the same he re-read the first three and he thought you know God these are really good books and they are in fact astounding works of literature and he wondered if he was up to snuff if he could still write like that And then he sat down and wrote two more. And they were very different than the first three, but they were as good. And, in fact, some people liked them better. I guess it's a matter of preference, but I think what you heard was a writer just thinking to himself. Okay, I can think... I read a little bit of the work that he's... the thing that he's working on now, and there's some tremendous stuff in there. Okay, I can think of one more. This is sort of a personal opinion question, too, just between two Jack Vance fans. I suppose any writer has to put some of himself into his characters. You mentioned that maybe there's a little of Vance in Kugel, for instance. In my reading of his work, I would say that maybe in the Durdayn trilogy, the protagonist, Gastel Etzwein, of all the characters Vance has written about, to me, that would seem closest to what I would conceive of him as being. How would you respond to that? Yeah, you've got it there, and also there's a lot of Vance in Inferio in The Man and His Son, you know, because Jack and Norma are both very close to their son, John, and Inferio, in a sense, was kind of written, I think, for John to read at some later date in his life. John the son John doesn't John doesn't read any of his father's books and I think Jack wrote that book for John and and I would say yes I'd say Dardin Jack likes that series a lot they're really mature works yeah there's a lot of them in there because Jack as a musician and I just the musician going on to the world and finding things out about himself and the world around him. But Cugol also. Jack's a bit of a rascal, and that part of him happens to be Cugol. Are you going to do Dernayn, by the way? Yeah. I'm looking forward to that one. That's probably my favorite. Yeah. Yeah, some people feel that way. People really like that series. You're right when you said it was a mature work, I think that very subtle... Listen, our connection is kind of getting bad now anyhow, and I think that's probably all the time we better... Just a second, David has... Oh, David wants to know if you're going to do the hardcover of Lioness ever. Yeah, as a matter of fact we're planning to do that because Berkeley is probably going to issue it as a trade paperback so if it works out, yes we are going to do a hardcover addition of that. And so, theoretically, yours would be the first hardcover? Yeah, it'll be the first edition also if we can precede them. Yeah. And it'll be a small edition probably. 700 copies, whatever. Yeah, we're going to stay on your mailing list then. Good. Listen, we sure appreciate your time again. Thank you very much, Tim. Good. Okay. Yeah. Okay? If you have any other questions or whatever, just call me home or call Chuck here. We might do that. Thank you. Yeah, very good. Take care. Bye. Bye.
